<h3>Neurotrophic Factor Mimicry</h3>

<p>The core mechanism is straightforward. Cerebrolysin's peptide fragments mimic the activity of BDNF (brain-derived neurotrophic factor), NGF (nerve growth factor), and GDNF (glial cell-derived neurotrophic factor). These are the proteins your brain naturally produces to grow and maintain neurons.</p>

<p>Hartbauer et al. (2001) demonstrated that Cerebrolysin activates the PI3K/Akt and MAPK/ERK signaling pathways (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11358484/">PubMed</a>). These are the same downstream cascades triggered by actual BDNF binding.</p>

<table class="tbl">
<thead><tr><th>Factor Mimicked</th><th>Normal Role</th><th>Cerebrolysin Effect</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>BDNF</strong></td><td>Neuron survival and growth</td><td class="g">Activates PI3K/Akt and MAPK/ERK</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>NGF</strong></td><td>Neuronal maintenance</td><td class="g">Promotes neuronal health</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>GDNF</strong></td><td>Dopaminergic neuron protection</td><td class="g">Supports dopamine pathways</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Neuroplasticity and Synaptic Density</h3>

<p>Rockenstein et al. (2006) found that Cerebrolysin increases synaptophysin, a marker of synaptic density (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16697710/">PubMed</a>). More synapses means more connections between neurons.</p>

<p>That translates to better cognitive function and faster recovery from brain injuries. It's the same principle behind why exercise and environmental enrichment improve cognition.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Finding</div>
  <p>Cerebrolysin increases synaptophysin levels while simultaneously shifting APP processing away from toxic amyloid beta production. This dual action makes it relevant for both acute brain injuries and chronic neurodegenerative disease (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16697710/">Rockenstein et al., 2006</a>).</p>
</div>

<h3>Anti-inflammatory Effects</h3>

<p>Alvarez et al. (2006) showed that Cerebrolysin reduces microglial activation and lowers TNF-alpha and IL-1 beta levels (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16439158/">PubMed</a>). Chronic neuroinflammation is a driver of nearly every neurodegenerative condition.</p>

<p>By calming the brain's immune response, Cerebrolysin creates a more favorable environment for healing and neuronal survival.</p>

<!-- ========== CLINICAL EVIDENCE ========== -->
